Diamond Problem in Java
=======================
The Diamond Problem occurs in multiple inheritance when a class inherits from two interfaces/classes that
both define the same method, creating ambiguity about which implementation to use.

Interface A
        default void hello()
       /            \
  Interface B      Interface C
  default void hello()  default void hello()
       \            /
        Class D (ambiguous!)

Problem:
-------
interface A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from A");
    }
}

interface B extends A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from B");
    }
}

interface C extends A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from C");
    }
}

// ❌ Compile Error — ambiguous — which hello() to use?
class D implements B, C {
}

Java's 3 Resolution Rules: Java resolves diamond conflicts using these rules in order:
Rule 1 — Classes win over Interfaces
------
If a superclass provides a concrete method, it wins over any interface default.

class Base {
    public void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from Base class");
    }
}

interface A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from A");
    }
}

// Base class method wins — no ambiguity
class D extends Base implements A {
}

new D().hello(); // "Hello from Base class"

Rule 2 — Most Specific Interface Wins: one interface extends another, the more specific (child) interface wins.

interface A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from A");
    }
}

interface B extends A {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from B"); // more specific
    }
}

// B is more specific than A — B wins
class D implements A, B {
}

new D().hello(); // "Hello from B"


Rule 3 — Explicitly Override (Mandatory): If two sibling interfaces (neither extends the other) define the same default, the implementing class must override and resolve manually.
------
interface B {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from B");
    }
}

interface C {
    default void hello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from C");
    }
}

class D implements B, C {

    @Override
    public void hello() {
        // Option 1: Custom implementation
        System.out.println("Hello from D");

        // Option 2: Explicitly delegate to B
        B.super.hello();

        // Option 3: Explicitly delegate to C
        C.super.hello();

        // Option 4: Call both
        B.super.hello();
        C.super.hello();
    }
}
